Regression

Summary

The goal is to learn how to build and interpret linear regression models using the mtcars data set.

Methods

These are the statistics we will use to evaluate prediction accuracy for a continuous variable:

  • Mean absolute error
  • Mean squared error
  • Root mean squared error
  • Mean absolute percentage error

There are various methods to evaluate and interpret a linear regression model.

  • Adjusted R squared
  • Variance inflation factor
  • AIC
  • BIC

Evaluating the distribution of residuals.

  • Cooks distance
  • Q-Q plot
  • Heteroscedasticity

Model comparisons.

  • Anova
  • k-Fold Cross Validation

Analysis

R libraries

We need a couple of libraries for the exercises. Lets load them all upfront:

library(ggplot2)
library(caret)
library(broom)
library(DMwR)
library(car)

library(boot)

Splitting training and testing data set

We first create a training and testing data set.

set.seed(303)
data(mtcars)
print(head(mtcars))
##                    mpg cyl disp  hp drat    wt  qsec vs am gear carb
## Mazda RX4         21.0   6  160 110 3.90 2.620 16.46  0  1    4    4
## Mazda RX4 Wag     21.0   6  160 110 3.90 2.875 17.02  0  1    4    4
## Datsun 710        22.8   4  108  93 3.85 2.320 18.61  1  1    4    1
## Hornet 4 Drive    21.4   6  258 110 3.08 3.215 19.44  1  0    3    1
## Hornet Sportabout 18.7   8  360 175 3.15 3.440 17.02  0  0    3    2
## Valiant           18.1   6  225 105 2.76 3.460 20.22  1  0    3    1
train = createDataPartition(y = mtcars$mpg, p=0.8, list=F)
training = mtcars[train,]
testing = mtcars[-train,]
print(dim(training))
## [1] 28 11
print(dim(testing))
## [1]  4 11

Building a linear model

Now lets build a linear model using one response (outcome) variable, named mpg, and two predictor variables, named wt and disp.

model1 = lm(mpg ~ wt + disp, data=training)
pander(summary(model1))
Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)
(Intercept) 35.04 2.501 14.01 2.44e-13
wt -3.496 1.317 -2.654 0.01362
disp -0.01528 0.01028 -1.487 0.1496
Fitting linear model: mpg ~ wt + disp
Observations Residual Std. Error \(R^2\) Adjusted \(R^2\)
28 3.001 0.7665 0.7478

Predict on the testing data

Next, lets predict on the testing data using our linear model and evaluate the accuracy of the predictions.

pred1 = predict(model1, newdata=testing)
pander(data.frame(prediction=pred1, truth=testing$mpg))
prediction truth
Mazda RX4 23.43 21
Duster 360 17.05 14.3
Dodge Challenger 17.87 15.5
Lotus Europa 28.29 30.4 
mae = sum(abs(testing$mpg - pred1)) / nrow(testing)
mse = mean((testing$mpg - pred1)^2)
rmse = sqrt(mse)
mape = mean(abs(testing$mpg - pred1) / testing$mpg)
print(c(mae, mse, rmse, mape))
## [1] 2.4143073 5.8813658 2.4251527 0.1325586
DMwR::regr.eval(testing$mpg, pred1)
##       mae       mse      rmse      mape 
## 2.4143073 5.8813658 2.4251527 0.1325586

Interpreting the regression model

There are various methods to evaluate a regression model.

model1 = lm(mpg ~ wt + disp, data=training)
pander(summary(model1))
Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)
(Intercept) 35.04 2.501 14.01 2.44e-13
wt -3.496 1.317 -2.654 0.01362
disp -0.01528 0.01028 -1.487 0.1496
Fitting linear model: mpg ~ wt + disp
Observations Residual Std. Error \(R^2\) Adjusted \(R^2\)
28 3.001 0.7665 0.7478 
print(c(AIC(model1), BIC(model1)))
## [1] 145.8316 151.1604
print(car::vif(model1))
##       wt     disp 
## 5.028637 5.028637

The variance inflation factor suggests that wt and disp are highly correlated.

ggplot(data=mtcars, aes(x=wt, y=disp)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method="lm")

print(cor(mtcars$wt, mtcars$disp))
## [1] 0.8879799

We could try to improve the model by dropping disp and adding qseq

model2 = lm(mpg ~ wt + qsec, data=training)
pander(summary(model2))

Building better models

We could now brute force iterate all possible models. The leaps package has a function to extract best subsets.

sub = regsubsets(mpg ~ log(wt) + qsec + disp + cyl + hp + drat,data = mtcars)
plot(sub, scale="adjr2")

Our previous model still has the best adjusted R-squared. We can also include interaction terms.

sub = regsubsets(mpg ~ log(wt) * qsec * hp, data = mtcars)
plot(sub, scale="adjr2")

plot(sub, scale="bic")

model4 = lm(mpg ~ log(wt) + qsec + log(wt):hp + qsec:hp, data = mtcars)
car::residualPlots(model4)

Lastly, we could stepwise build a best model.

mtcars$lwt = log(mtcars$wt)
lowmod = lm(mpg ~ 1, data=mtcars)
upmod = lm(mpg ~ ., data=mtcars)
model5 = step(lowmod, scope=list(lower=lowmod, upper=upmod), direction="both", trace=1, steps=1000)

Model Comparisons

We can use Anova to evaluate if adding more predictors is performing significantly better compared to the previous model.

m1 = lm(mpg ~ log(wt), data=mtcars)
m2 = lm(mpg ~ log(wt) + qsec, data=mtcars)
m3 = lm(mpg ~ log(wt) + qsec + log(wt):hp, data=mtcars)
m4 = lm(mpg ~ log(wt) + qsec + log(wt):hp + qsec:hp, data = mtcars)
anova(m1, m2, m3, m4)

We can also use k-Fold Cross Validation to compute the mean squared error.

m1 = glm(mpg ~ log(wt), data=mtcars)
m2 = glm(mpg ~ log(wt) + qsec, data=mtcars)
m3 = glm(mpg ~ log(wt) + qsec + log(wt):hp, data=mtcars)
m4 = glm(mpg ~ log(wt) + qsec + log(wt):hp + qsec:hp, data = mtcars)
cv.m1.err = cv.glm(mtcars, m1, K=5)$delta
print(cv.m1.err)
## [1] 8.140930 7.973093
cv.m2.err = cv.glm(mtcars, m2, K=5)$delta
print(cv.m2.err)
## [1] 5.263380 5.155458
cv.m3.err = cv.glm(mtcars, m3, K=5)$delta
print(cv.m3.err)
## [1] 5.256126 5.147315
cv.m4.err = cv.glm(mtcars, m4, K=5)$delta
print(cv.m4.err)
## [1] 4.892757 4.734068
